# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: donald-i-siegel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Headquartered in New York City, the company ranked 394th in the 2016 annual ranking of Fortune 500 corporations.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 2020, the *Forbes* Global 2000 ranked Hess as the 1,253rd largest public company in the world.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The company had exploration and production operations on-shore in the United States (North Dakota) and Libya; and off-shore in the United States (Gulf of Mexico), Canada, South America (Guyana and Suriname) and Southeast Asia (Malaysia and the Joint Development Area of Malaysia and Thailand).
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1919, British oil entrepreneur Lord Cowdray formed the **Amerada Corporation** to explore oil production in North America.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The firm was incorporated on February 7, 1920, in Delaware as a holding company for its principal subsidiary, the **Amerada Petroleum Corporation**.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The oil producer experienced growth during most of the 1920s, hitting a peak in 1926 with a net income of US$4.9 million.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] However, in the years leading to the Great Depression, weakness in the oil markets contributed to sluggish profits.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The aftermath of the Wall Street Crash of 1929 aggravated an already unsteady oil industry.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In the first quarter of 1930, the company experienced a minor loss.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The early years of the Depression were a struggle against wavering demand and overproduction in some regions.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Later into the 1930s, financial forecasts for Amerada became more positive.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In December 1941, the company reorganized by merging the holding company and the principal operating subsidiary, Amerada Petroleum Corporation, into a simplified operating company.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The new entity also adopted the former subsidiary's name.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] During the 1950s, the company expanded into pipelining and refining.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1951, it discovered oil in the Bakken formation near Tioga, North Dakota.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1955, robust post-war growth grew the company to over US$100 million in annual sales.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1964, Amerada, Shell plc, Marathon, and Continental formed the Oasis Group, a consortium to explore in Libya.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess Oil and Chemical was founded in 1933 by Leon Hess as an operation out of Asbury Park, New Jersey that sold refining leftovers to hotels as heating fuel.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1938, he purchased land in Perth Amboy for his first oil storage terminal and in 1958 opened the company's first refinery, located in Port Reading.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The company went public in 1962 after merging with the Cletrac Corporation, a company that made farm equipment.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In October 1966, the company opened an oil refinery on Saint Croix of the US Virgin Islands under Hess Oil Virgin Islands Corporation.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1966, Hess paid $100 million to the British government to acquire 10% of Amerada.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Albert Levinson became the senior vice president and designed the modern-day Hess logo.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In December 1968, Hess and Amerada announced plans for a merger.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Some Amerada stockholders, led by Morton Adler, criticized the arrangement as being too favorable for Hess.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Before the stockholder vote, Phillips Petroleum, an integrated oil firm, approached Amerada with its merger proposal, but the offer was declined in March 1969.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Still interested, Phillips nonetheless stated it would not carry out a lawsuit against the proposed Hess deal.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess, fearing such a strategy, made a cash tender offer of US$140 million for an additional 1.1 million shares of Amerada, which would double its holding in the company.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The new claims would be employed in a May stockholder vote deciding the merger's fate.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The voting took place amidst shareholder rancor that, in addition to echoing Adler's arguments, objected to Amerada's financing of the recently completed tender offer.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess planned to cancel the shares, and the newly formed company would absorb the cost of the acquisition.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] One shareholder at the meeting quipped, "It looks to me as if Hess is buying Amerada with Amerada's money." Proponents of the deal won and the $2.4 billion merger combining a pure production company with a refinery and marketer operation was completed.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] However, the controversy was not yet extinguished.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] A federal class-action lawsuit was filed in 1972, which claimed that the proxy vote information was misleading.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1976, a court agreed that the company falsely claimed to have considered each company's assets as a reason for the merger.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In May 1970, Amerada Hess drilled the first successful wildcat well in Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's North Slope.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In August, it joined with seven other companies to form Alyeska Pipeline Service Company in order to build and operate the $900‐million, 800‐mile Trans-Alaska Pipeline System.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In October 1970, Hess stepped down from his role as chairman and CEO.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] However, after profits declined, he took back his roles in August 1972.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The company's president and executive vice president resigned.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In October 1974, Hess announced it would close its refinery in Port Reading, New Jersey.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] To compensate, the company would expand its activities at its Virgin Islands and Mississippi locations, including an $18 million container port in St.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In December 1981, Hess joined with Mobil in its bid to acquire Marathon and avoid antitrust concerns.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] However the deal ultimately fell through and United States Steel Corporation proved to be the winning bid.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess stepped down from his role as CEO in May 1982.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Company president Philip Kramer replaced him, while Hess remained chairman.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In November 1985, the company acquired the London-based Monsanto Oil Company from Monsanto to increase its interests in two oilfields in the North Sea.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In July 1988, Amerada Hess announced it would acquire Whitehall Ltd., a British oil and gas exploration company, from Pearson PLC for $160 million.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The deal included Whitehall's interests in the Ivanhoe, Rob Roy, Waverley, Forties, Alba, and Anglia oil fields, as well as significant North Sea gas reserves.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In September 1990, Amerada Hess acquired British Petroleum's stake in Norway's Brage oil field, which was due to start producing in 1994.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The company closed a Mississippi refinery in January 1994, eliminating 160 jobs.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In October, Amerada Hess formed a joint venture with Gabon to gain access to the Rabi-Kounga oil field.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1995, Hess stepped down as chairman and CEO of the company, and was replaced by his son, John Hess.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In April 1996, Petro-Canada paid $538 million to Amerada Hess Corp. for all shares of its Amerada Hess Canada Ltd subsidiary.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In May, Hess announced it would sell nine United States oil and natural gas fields and use the expected $324 million in proceeds to pay off debt.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] It also allowed the company to focus on its more profitable operations in the Virgin Islands and North Sea.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In February 1998, Hess sold 50% of its Virgin Islands refinery for $625 million.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Operations were taken over by Hovensa LLC, a joint venture between Hess and the Venezuelan state-owned PDVSA.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In February 2000, Hess acquired the Meadville Corporation and rebranded all 178 Merit gas stations as Hess.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The Merit gas station chain was primarily located in the Boston, New York, and Philadelphia markets.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In April, the company spent $555 million for a 49% stake in the state-owned Sonatrach to develop the El Gassi, El Agreb and Zotti fields in Algeria.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In July 2001, Amerada Hess purchased Triton Energy Limited for $2.6 billion in order to put more focus on exploration.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] After the deal, the company's oil production increased to 535,000 barrels a day and 38% of its reserves were outside of the US and North Sea.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Triton's major oil and gas assets in West Africa, Latin America and Southeast Asia would strengthen its exploration and production business and provide access to long life international reserves.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess also stated that the purchase was expected to immediately increase the company's per-day barrel output by more than 25 percent.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Similarly in 2001, Amerada Hess entered into a joint venture with A.T.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Williams Oil Co. of Winston-Salem, North Carolina.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The company and the gas stations were changed and called WilcoHess.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] After the joint merger, there existed some 1200 WilcoHess stations.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Following on the heels of the Triton purchase, energy prices fell and global economies weakened.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Amerada Hess struggled through the following years, and in 2002 posted a US$218 million loss due primarily to a US$530 million charge relating to its write-down of the Ceiba oil field.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In March 2002, TXU Europe bought the UK retail gas and electricity business of Amerada Hess.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] It also sold its 1.5 percent stake in the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System to ConocoPhillips in February 2003.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In2June, the company 6 oil and gas fields in the Gulf of Mexico to the Anadarko Petroleum Corporation and agreed to trade some properties with the EnCana Corporation.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Further, Amerada Hess cut exploration and production jobs by 30 percent and reduced office space in Aberdeen, Scotland, and London.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] However, from 2003 through 2006, Amerada Hess posted steadily increasing profits as the company reported US$1.920 billion in net income.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In May 2006, Amerada Hess Corporation changed its name to Hess Corporation.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In May 2010, Hess announced a joint venture with Toreador Resources of France to develop Toreador's one million gross acres in France's Paris Basin.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In July, Hess announced it would acquire the independent American Oil & Gas for $445 million.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In the first half of 2013, Hess was subjected to a proxy battle against activist investor Elliott Associates, which owned 4% of its stock at the time.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Elliott criticized Hess for being "distracted" from oil exploration and production by other activities, wasting capital, and relying too heavily on the Hess family and their allies.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In January 2013, Elliott announced its intentions to acquire additional Hess stock.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] It also called on Hess to sell certain assets and asked Hess investors to vote for five new directors as part of an effort to reconfigure the oil firm and thus boost its share price.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] "Buried within Hess Corp. is one of the premier U.S. resource play-focused companies," Elliott wrote.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Another Hess stockholder, Relational Investors, came out in support of Elliott.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] A point of contention was that several members of the company's board were close associates of the Hess family and did not have experience in oil.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] These included former New Jersey governor Thomas Kean, former Georgia senator Samuel A.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Nunn, and Gregory Hill, the president of worldwide exploration and production for Hess.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Elliott announced five candidates for board seats.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In March, Hess announced that it was acting on some of Elliott's suggestions.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] It replaced six directors, raised its dividends, and introduced a stock buyback.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The company also announced its plan to sell off the Hess stations division and all other consumer-facing endeavors.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] However, Elliott said that Hess' changes fell far short of what was needed.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In April, it was reported that Hess would close its London office on Elliott's advice.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] By May, Elliott had the support of influential advisors Institutional Shareholder Services and Glass Lewis.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The company announced it would split the chief executive and president roles in a move to appease shareholders.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] A deal was finally reached hours before the company's annual investor meeting with shareholders.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess agreed to give Elliott three board seats if it supported the company's five nominees.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] As of the fourth quarter of 2014, Elliott owned 17.8 million shares of Hess, worth $1.3 billion, making it Elliott's largest holding.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] On January 18, 2012, the company announced that it would close the Hovensa refinery in St.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Croix, United States Virgin Islands by mid-February 2012.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The refinery would continue to serve as a storage terminal.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess took a $525 million charge against its fourth-quarter 2011 earnings due to the shutdown.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In May, the company sold its 15.67% interest in Schiehallion oil field, North Sea, to Royal Dutch Shell.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In January 2013, Hess announced its plan to sell off its network of 19 storage terminals located on the East Coast and St.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] By the end of February 2013, and while Elliott waged its proxy fight, Hess permanently closed its Port Reading, New Jersey petroleum refinery.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Gas prices had risen to their highest levels since October 2012 and Hess said it would lay off 170 of 217 employees at the plant, exit the refinery business and look for a buyer for its 19 storage terminals.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] It also noted that Hess would sell its holdings in Indonesia and Thailand.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In April 2013, Hess Corp announced it would be selling its Russian unit to Lukoil for $2.05 billion.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In July 2013, Hess Corp said it would sell its energy marketing unit to UK firm Centrica for around $1.03 billion.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In July 2013, Hess agreed to sell its wholesale and retail oil, natural gas and electricity marketing business to Direct Energy.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In October 2013, Hess Corp announced it would sell its East Coast and St.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Lucia storage terminal network to Buckeye Partners LP for $850 million.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In December 2013, Hess Corp announced that it was selling its Indonesian assets to an Indonesian petroleum consortium.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] On January 8, 2014, Hess filed for a tax-free spin-off of its gas station network.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The newly formed company was to be known as Hess Retail and would include over 1,200 stores throughout the Eastern United States.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Before completing the spin-off, Marathon Petroleum subsidiary Speedway LLC announced on May 22, 2014, that it would acquire the retail unit of Hess Corp for $2.87 billion.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Following the closure of the acquisition in late 2014, it was announced that all Hess gas stations were to be rebranded as Speedway gas stations by the end of 2017, although a few stations ended up taking on another company.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The company also sold its 50% interests in the Bayonne Energy Center and Newark Energy Center, as well as its 50% interest in Hess Energy Trading Company (HETCO) to Oaktree Capital.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] As of October 2014, Hess had completed its multi-year transformation of exiting all downstream operations, and was a solely an exploration and production company; doing generated $13 billion for the company.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In April 2015, ExxonMobil announced its discovery of a significant oil reserve off the coast of Guyana in South America.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] At the time, it was estimated to contain more than 700 million barrels of oil.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess began acquiring interest in the reserve in 2018.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] By 2022, estimates were increased to 11 billion barrels.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In October 2023, Chevron Corporation announced that it would acquire Hess Corporation in an all-stock deal for $53 billion, or $60 billion including debt.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Since this would give Chevron control of Hess' 30% interest in the Guyana oil fields, Exxon protested and claimed to have a right of first refusal to acquire those assets.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In March 2024, Exxon and CNOOC, the third partner in the offshore Stabroek block, filed arbitration cases with the International Chamber of Commerce to stop the deal.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess shareholders, meanwhile, approved the acquisition that May.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The arbitration hearing was heard in May 2025.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In September 2024, under the Biden Administration, the Federal Trade Commission conditioned approval of the merger upon John B.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] On July 18, 2025, Chevron reported that it completed its purchase of Hess Corporation and Hess was subsequently appointed to Chevron's board of directors.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess outlined in its 2006 Corporate Sustainability Report a "four-element" strategy to reduce and control greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The strategy's steps included monitoring, measuring, managing, and mitigating the emissions.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The company intends to improve its environmental impact through reporting results, increasing energy efficiency and recovery, and participating in carbon capture and trading.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In December 2022, the company was added to the Dow Jones Sustainability World Index.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In August 1976, 600 gallons of oil seeped into the Arthur Kill and Raritan River when a barge heading to Hess' Perth Amboy facility struck a rock.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] A month later, Amerada Hess and eight other oil companies that operated in the area, announced plans to form a mutual aid cooperative that would clean up major oil spills in the harbor.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] On October 28, 1990, a barge containing 31,000 barrels (4,900 m3) of kerosene struck a reef in the Hudson River, spilling 163,000 US gallons (620 m3) of fuel.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Immediately, Hess assumed responsibility for the cleanup; the Coast Guard worked alongside the barge's owner to clean and contain the spill.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Coast Guard official Howard Holmes said that 70 percent of the spill would be gone in three days due to the natural evaporation rate of kerosene.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Even though most kerosene evaporates, toxic chemicals such as benzene stay in the water and harm fish.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In September 1990, 5,000 gallons of oil spilled into the Arthur Kill when a six million-gallon Hess Oil tank at the company's Perth Amboy Terminal collapsed.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The agreement was aimed at resolving Hess's violations in the DEC's New York City and lower Hudson Valley regions.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In April 2012, a Hess pipeline burst near Pennsauken, New Jersey.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] While most of the oil spilled into a containment ditch, approximately 100 gallons went into the Delaware River.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Following the Exxon Valdez oil spill in March 1989, the State of Alaska sued Amerada Hess and the other operators of Alyeska Pipeline Service Company for damages done to the Prince William Sound and the region's fisheries-based economy.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1992, Alyeska paid $31.3 million to settle state and Federal claims for damages to the natural resources.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In July 1993, the companies agreed to pay $98 million to native Alaskans.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In June 2005, Hess evacuated its Breton Sound 51 platform in advance of Tropical Storm Arlene.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Upon returning, workers discovered a damaged storage tank that leaked 500 gallons of oil into the Gulf of Mexico just off of Louisiana.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] When oil washed ashore on a rookery on nearby West Breton Island, part of the Breton National Wildlife Refuge, 450 endangered brown pelicans were killed.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] When including future generations that would have existed if not for the spill, it was estimated that over 1,300 fledgling pelicans were lost.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] More than 300 pelicans were washed and rehabilitated over the next three months.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In November 2018, Hess agreed to pay $8.7 million to settle a federal and state lawsuit over the spill.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The money was added to the $72 million plan to rebuild North Breton Island following the BP oil spill.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In a 2008 water contamination case against several major US oil companies, the Hess Corporation was forced to pay part of a $422 million settlement.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The case was filed by 153 public water providers in 17 states against the oil companies "over drinking water contamination caused by the gasoline additive Methyl Tertiary Butyl Ether (MTBE)".
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The settlement also stipulated that the settling parties pay their share of treatment costs of the plaintiffs' wells that may become contaminated or require treatment for the next 30 years.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In February 2015, Hess reported over 40,000 gallons of spilled brine between two well sites about three miles apart in North Dakota.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Both were caused by opened valves, which the company referred to as acts of vandalism.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In July 2016, Hess reported a 32,000-gallon spill of produced water north of Tioga, North Dakota.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In March 2021, Hess paid a fine for a Clean Water Act violation stemming from an October 2015 inspection at its Tioga gas plant.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In August 2022, a North Dakota pipeline owned by Hess experienced a wastewater spill.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Originally reported by the company as a 200-barrel spill from August 12, investigators determined that it was actually closer to a 34,000-barrel spill dating back to three weeks prior with evidence of groundwater contamination.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] On December 5, 2022, more than 7,800 gallons of propylene glycol and more than 4,400 gallons of produced water spilled from a Hess pipeline near Ray, North Dakota.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The Hess refinery facility in the US Virgin Islands opened in the 1960s.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] By 1982, the company identified underground contamination that ultimately released at least 300,000 barrels of petrochemicals into the groundwater and polluted the island's aquifer.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Recovery and treatment wells began pumping in 1987 to reclaim the oil that had been lost.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In September 1989, the facility was hit by Hurricane Hugo, resulting in two major oil spills on the island of St.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Roughly 10,000 barrels of oil were discharged from damaged storage tanks at the Hess Oil Virgin Islands Corporation, and 14,000 barrels of oil were discharged from the Virgin Islands Water and Power Authority facility in Christiansted.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1994, the EPA determined the facility's underground pipes needed to be replaced.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In the following years, benzene was vented into the air and mercury was flushed down drains.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] By 2008, nearly 42 million gallons of free product petroleum had been reclaimed from the on-site groundwater.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In December 1996, the company was fined $5.3 million for illegally shipping hazardous waste from the Virgin Islands to Arizona in 1991 and 1992.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess ultimately halted operations in 2012 and converted the site into a storage facility.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Virgin Islands sued the company in 2015 for $1 billion for environmental damages, Hess's Hovensa facility declared bankruptcy.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] This meant it did not pay for a full cleanup and only paid $4.7 million to settle four class-action suits.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In December 2023, Hess Corporation was ordered to pay $150 million to hundreds of former St.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Croix refinery workers and their families who were injured by asbestos exposure.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In January 2024, a group of three Americans filed a class action lawsuit accusing Hess, along with seven other US oil and gas producers, of an illegal price-fixing scheme.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The plaintiffs alleged attempts to constrain production of shale oil that led to consumers in the US paying more for gasoline for their auto transportation than they would have in a competitive market.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Before the March 4, 2013 announcement of its withdrawal from refining and retail sales of petroleum products, Hess operated gas stations across the US.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In May 2014, Speedway LLC, a subsidiary of Marathon Petroleum Company, announced it would purchase Hess Corporation's retail business for $2.6 billion.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Hess had 1,342 locations across the Eastern United States.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] The conversion from Hess branding to Speedway branding took place over the course of 2015.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] This also included all the WilcoHess locations, which Hess had acquired outright shortly before exiting the retail business.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] Subsequently, in 2016 Speedway and Pilot Flying J entered into a joint venture called PFJ Southeast LLC, which manages all of the former WilcoHess truck stops; the locations are managed by Pilot and were rebranded as either Pilot or Flying J.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] As of 2018, Hess locations remained in a few states including Connecticut and Pennsylvania.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 2021, 7-Eleven acquired Speedway from Marathon, bringing the former Hess locations into the fold.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] In 1964, Hess Oil and Chemical began selling a toy tanker truck at its gas stations.
[src:donald-i-siegel/amerada-hess-corporation] This release would become a series of toy trucks and other vehicles released before Christmas each year, sold through gas station locations and online.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS was the first permanent organization established to promote science and engineering nationally and to represent the interests of American researchers from across all scientific fields.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is the world's largest general scientific society, with over 120,000 members, and is the publisher of the well-known scientific journal *Science*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The American Association for the Advancement of Science was created on September 20, 1848, at the Academy of Natural Sciences in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] According to the first constitution which was agreed to at the September 20 meeting, the goal of the society was to promote scientific dialogue in order to allow for greater scientific collaboration.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By doing so, the association aimed to use resources to conduct science with increased efficiency and allow for scientific progress at a greater rate.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The association also sought to increase the resources available to the scientific community through active advocacy of science.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There were only 78 members when the AAAS was formed.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As a member of the new scientific body, Matthew Fontaine Maury, USN was one of those who attended the first 1848 meeting.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] At a meeting held on Friday afternoon, September 22, 1848, Redfield presided, and Matthew Fontaine Maury gave a full scientific report on his *Wind and Current Charts*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Maury stated that hundreds of ship navigators were now sending abstract logs of their voyages to the United States Naval Observatory.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He added, "Never before was such a corps of observers known." But, he pointed out to his fellow scientists, his critical need was for more "simultaneous observations".
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] "The work," Maury stated, "is not exclusively for the benefit of any nation or age".
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Coffin of Easton, Pennsylvania, and Professor Stephen Alexander of Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] This was scientific cooperation, and Maury went back to Washington with great hopes for the future.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1850, the first female members were accepted: astronomer Maria Mitchell and entomologist Margaretta Morris.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Science educator Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps was elected in 1859.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By 1860, membership increased to over 2,000.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Although the AAAS became dormant during the American Civil War (their August 1861 meeting in Nashville, Tennessee, was postponed indefinitely after the outbreak of the first major engagement of the war at Bull Run), the association recovered after the end of the hostilities.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1866, Frederick Barnard presided over the first meeting of the resurrected AAAS at a meeting in New York City.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Following the revival of the AAAS, the group had considerable growth.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS permitted all people, regardless of scientific credentials, to join.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS did, however, institute a policy of granting the title of "Fellow of the AAAS" to well-respected scientists within the organization.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Also, the reputation of the AAAS was somewhat tarnished, because its 3rd president Alexander Dallas Bache used the Society as a lobbying tool for his agency, the US Coast Survey.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Several prominent scientists lost interest in the AAAS, and the society's influence declined.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next turning point in the AAAS history was the partnership with journal *Science*, which became the society's official publication in 1900, and provided the AAAS with some revenue through subscription and advertising.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS become the sole owner of *Science* in 1946.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Another important event for the society was the establishment of its Congressional Fellowship program in 1973, which was kick-started by a US$10,000 donation from William T.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Leshner, AAAS CEO from 2001 until 2015, published many op-ed articles discussing how many people integrate science and religion in their lives.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He has opposed the insertion of non-scientific content, such as creationism or intelligent design, into the scientific curriculum of schools.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In February 2007, the AAAS used satellite images to document human rights abuses in Burma.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next year, AAAS launched the Center for Science Diplomacy to advance both science and the broader relationships among partner countries, by promoting science diplomacy and international scientific cooperation.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 2012, AAAS published op-eds, held events on Capitol Hill and released analyses of the U.S. federal research-and-development budget, to warn that a budget sequestration would have severe consequences for scientific progress.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS covers various areas of sciences and engineering.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It has 24 sections, each with a committee and its chair.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These committees are also entrusted with the annual evaluation and selection of Fellows.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The most recent Constitution of the AAAS, enacted on January 1, 1973, establishes that the governance of the AAAS is accomplished through four entities: a President, a group of administrative officers, a Council, and a board of directors.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Individuals elected to the presidency of the AAAS hold a three-year term in a unique way.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The first year is spent as president-elect, the second as president and the third as chairperson of the board of directors.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In accordance with the convention followed by the AAAS, presidents are referenced by the year in which they left office.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Geraldine Richmond is the president of AAAS for 2015–16; Phillip Sharp is the board chair; and Barbara A.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each took office on the last day of the 2015 AAAS Annual Meeting in February 2015.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] On the last day of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, February 15, 2016, Richmond will become the chair, Schaal will become the president, and a new president-elect will take office.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Past presidents of AAAS have included some of the most important scientific figures of their time.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among them: explorer and geologist John Wesley Powell (1888); astronomer and physicist Edward Charles Pickering (1912); anthropologist Margaret Mead (1975); and biologist Stephen Jay Gould (2000).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There are three classifications of high-level administrative officials that execute the basic, daily functions of the AAAS.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These are the executive officer, the treasurer and then each of the AAAS's section secretaries.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current CEO of AAAS and executive publisher of *Science* magazine is Sudip Parikh.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current Editor in Chief of Science magazine is Holden Thorp.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS has 24 "sections" with each section being responsible for a particular concern of the AAAS.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS affiliates include 262 societies and academies of science, serving more than 10 million members, from the Acoustical Society of America to the Wildlife Society, as well as non-mainstream groups like the Parapsychological Association.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council is composed of the members of the Board of Directors, the retiring section chairmen, elected delegates and affiliated foreign council members.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among the elected delegates there are always at least two members from the National Academy of Sciences and one from each region of the country.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The President of the AAAS serves as the Chairperson of the council.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve the council for a term of three years.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council meets annually to discuss matters of importance to the AAAS.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They have the power to review all activities of the Association, elect new fellows, adopt resolutions, propose amendments to the Association's constitution and bylaws, create new scientific sections, and organize and aid local chapters of the AAAS.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The Council recently has new additions to it from different sections which include many youngsters as well.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] John Kerry of Chicago is the youngest American in the council and Akhil Ennamsetty of India is the youngest foreign council member.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors is composed of a chairperson, the president, and the president-elect along with eight elected directors, the executive officer of the association and up to two additional directors appointed by elected officers.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve a four-year term except for directors appointed by elected officers, who serve three-year terms.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current chairman is Gerald Fink, Margaret and Herman Sokol Professor at Whitehead Institute, MIT.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Fink will serve in the post until the end of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, 15 February 2016.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors has a variety of powers and responsibilities.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is charged with the administration of all association funds, publication of a budget, appointment of administrators, proposition of amendments, and determining the time and place of meetings of the national association.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board may also speak publicly on behalf of the association.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board must also regularly correspond with the council to discuss their actions.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS council elects every year, its members who are distinguished scientifically, to the grade of fellow (**FAAAS**).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Election to AAAS is an honor bestowed by their peers and elected fellows are presented with a certificate and rosette pin.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Formal meetings of the AAAS are numbered consecutively, starting with the first meeting in 1848.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Meetings were not held 1861–1865 during the American Civil War, and also 1942–1943 during World War II.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Since 1946, one meeting has occurred annually, now customarily in February.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each year, the AAAS gives out a number of honorary awards, most of which focus on science communication, journalism, and outreach – sometimes in partnership with other organizations.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards recognize "scientists, journalists, and public servants for significant contributions to science and to the public's understanding of science".
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards are presented each year at the association's annual meeting.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These policy fellows spend one or two years working for the executive (130 positions), legislative (5 positions) or judicial (1 position) branches.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society's flagship publication is *Science*, a weekly interdisciplinary scientific journal.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Other peer-reviewed journals published by the AAAS in the "*Science* family of journals" are *Science Signaling*, *Science Translational Medicine*, *Science Immunology*, *Science Robotics* and the interdisciplinary *Science Advances*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They also publish the non-peer-reviewed *Science & Diplomacy*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society previously published the review journal *Science Books & Films* (SB&F).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS also publishes on behalf of other organizations through the Science Partner Journals (SPJ) program, with a focus on online-only open access journals.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine is a philanthropically funded and editorially independent service for journalists and scientists.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its launch was announced in an October 27, 2017 article in Science by founding director Rick Weiss, former communications chief at the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy and science reporter at the Washington Post.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its stated mission is to increase the amount and quality of research-backed evidence in news stories by connecting U.S. journalists to scientists and to validated scientific information.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Reporters in the United States can access SciLine's services, which include expert-matching, general media briefings, expert quote sheets, and quick fact sheets.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As of July 2021, SciLine had fulfilled approximately 2,000 requests from 650 journalists through its expert-matching service.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine's financial supporters include the Quadrivium Foundation, the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, the John S. and James L.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Knight Foundation, the Rita Allen Foundation, and the Heinz Endowments.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1996, AAAS launched the **EurekAlert!** website, an editorially independent nonprofit news release distribution service covering all areas of science, medicine and technology.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! provides news in English, Spanish, French, German, Portuguese, Japanese, and, from 2007, in Chinese.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Working staff journalists and freelancers who meet eligibility guidelines can access the latest studies before publication and obtain embargoed information in compliance with the U.S.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Securities and Exchange Commission's Regulation Fair Disclosure policy.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By early 2018, more than 14,000 reporters from more than 90 countries have registered for free access to embargoed materials.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] More than 5,000 active public information officers from 2,300 universities, academic journals, government agencies, and medical centers are credentialed to provide new releases to reporters and the public through the system.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1998, European science organizations countered Eurekalert! with a press release distribution service AlphaGalileo.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! has fallen under criticism for lack of press release standards and for generating churnalism.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The **American Chemical Society** (**ACS**) is a scientific society based in the United States that supports scientific inquiry in the field of chemistry.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Founded in 1876 at New York University, the ACS currently has more than 262,000 members at all degree levels and in all fields of chemistry, chemical engineering, and related fields.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] It is one of the world's largest scientific societies by membership.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization and holds a congressional charter under Title 36 of the United States Code.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Its headquarters are located in Washington, D.C., and it has a large concentration of staff in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a source of scientific information through its peer-reviewed scientific journals, national conferences, and the Chemical Abstracts Service.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Its publications division produces over 90 scholarly journals including the prestigious *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, as well as the weekly trade magazine *Chemical & Engineering News*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS holds national meetings twice a year covering the complete field of chemistry and also holds smaller conferences concentrating on specific chemical fields or geographic regions.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The primary source of income of the ACS is the Chemical Abstracts Service, a provider of chemical databases worldwide.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS has student chapters in virtually every major university in the United States and outside the United States as well.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] These student chapters mainly focus on volunteering opportunities, career development, and the discussion of student and faculty research.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The organization also publishes textbooks, administers several national chemistry awards, provides grants for scientific research, and supports various educational and outreach activities.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In 1874, a group of American chemists gathered at the Joseph Priestley House to mark the 100th anniversary of Priestley's discovery of oxygen.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Two years later, on April 6, 1876, during a meeting of chemists at the University of the City of New York (now New York University) the American Chemical Society was founded.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The society received its charter of incorporation from the State of New York in 1877.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Although Chandler was a likely choice to become the society's first president because of his role in organizing the society, New York University chemistry professor John William Draper was elected as the first president of the society because of his national reputation.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Draper was a photochemist and pioneering photographer who had produced one of the first photographic portraits in 1840.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Chandler would later serve as president in 1881 and 1889.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In the ACS logo, originally designed in the early 20th century by Tiffany's Jewelers and used since 1909, a stylized symbol of a kaliapparat is used.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The *Journal of the American Chemical Society* was founded in 1879 to publish original chemical research.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] It was the first journal published by ACS and is still the society's flagship peer-reviewed publication.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In 1907, Chemical Abstracts was established as a separate journal (it previously appeared within JACS), which later became the Chemical Abstracts Service, a division of ACS that provides chemical information to researchers and others worldwide.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] *Chemical & Engineering News* is a weekly trade magazine that has been published by ACS since 1923.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The society adopted a new constitution aimed at nationalizing the organization in 1890.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In 1905, the American Chemical Society moved from New York City to Washington, D.C.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] ACS was reincorporated under a congressional charter in 1937.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Congress and signed by president Franklin D.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] ACS's headquarters moved to its current location in downtown Washington in 1941.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] ACS first established technical divisions in 1908 to foster the exchange of information among scientists who work in particular fields of chemistry or professional interests.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Divisional activities include organizing technical sessions at ACS meetings, publishing books and resources, administering awards and lectureships, and conducting other events.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The original five divisions were 1) organic chemistry, 2) industrial chemists and chemical engineers, 3) agricultural and food chemistry, 4) fertilizer chemistry, and 5) physical and inorganic chemistry.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, there are 32 technical divisions of ACS.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] This is the largest division of the Society.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] It marked its 100th anniversary in 2008.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The first Chair of the Division was Edward Curtis Franklin.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The Organic Division played a part in establishing Organic Syntheses, Inc. and Organic Reactions, Inc. and it maintains close ties to both organizations.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The symposia also honor national award winners, including the Arthur C.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Cope Award, Cope Scholar Award, James Flack Norris Award in Physical Organic Chemistry, Herbert C.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Brown Award for Creative Research in Synthetic Methods.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The Division helps to organize symposia at the international meeting called Pacifichem and it organizes the biennial National Organic Chemistry Symposium (NOS) which highlights recent advances in organic chemistry and hosts the Roger Adams Award address.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The Division also organizes corporate sponsorships to provide fellowships for PhD students and undergraduates.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] It also organizes the Graduate Research Symposium and manages award and travel grant programs for undergraduates.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Local sections were authorized in 1890 and are autonomous units of the American Chemical Society.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] They elect their own officers and select representatives to the national ACS organization.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Local sections also provide professional development opportunities for members, organize community outreach events, offer awards, and conduct other business.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The Rhode Island Section was the first local section of ACS, organized in 1891.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] There are currently 186 local sections of the American Chemical Society in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] International Chemical Sciences Chapters allow ACS members outside of the U.S. to organize locally for professional and scientific exchange.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] There are currently 36 International Chemical Sciences Chapters.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] ACS states that it offers teacher training to support the professional development of science teachers so they can better present chemistry in the classroom, foster the scientific curiosity of our nation's youth and encourage future generations to pursue scientific careers.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] As of 2009, Clifford and Kathryn Hach donated $33 million to ACS, to continue the work of the Hach Scientific Foundation in supporting high school chemistry teaching.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The Society sponsors the United States National Chemistry Olympiad (USNCO), a contest used to select the four-member team that represents the United States at the International Chemistry Olympiad (IChO).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS Division of Chemical Education provides standardized tests for various subfields of chemistry.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The two most commonly used tests are the undergraduate-level tests for general and organic chemistry.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Each of these tests consists of 70 multiple-choice questions, and gives students 110 minutes to complete the exam.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS also approves certified undergraduate programs in chemistry.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] A student who completes the required laboratory and course work—sometimes in excess of what a particular college may require for its Bachelor's degree—is considered by the Society to be well trained for professional work.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS coordinates two annual public awareness campaigns, National Chemistry Week and Chemists Celebrate Earth Week, as part of its educational outreach.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Since 1978 and 2003 respectively, the campaigns have been celebrated with a yearly theme, such as "Chemistry Colors Our World" (2015) and "Energy: Now and Forever!" (2013).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The GCI was founded in 1997 as an independent non-profit organization, by chemists Joe Breen and Dennis Hjeresen in cooperation with the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The Petroleum Research Fund (PRF) is an endowment fund administered by the ACS that supports advanced education and fundamental research in the petroleum and fossil fuel fields at non-profit institutions.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Several categories of grants are offered for various career levels and institutions.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The fund awarded more than $25 million in grants in 2007.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The PRF traces its origins to the acquisition of the Universal Oil Products laboratory by a consortium of oil companies in 1931.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The companies established a trust fund, The Petroleum Research Fund, in 1944 to prevent antitrust litigation tied to their UOP assets.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS was named the beneficiary of the trust.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The first grants from the PRF were awarded in 1954.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In 2000, the trust was transferred to the ACS.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS established The American Chemical Society Petroleum Research Fund and the previous trust was dissolved.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The PRF trust was valued at $144.7 million in December 2014.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS International Activities is the birthplace of the ACS International Center, an online resource for scientists and engineers looking to study abroad or explore an international career or internship.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The site houses information on hundreds of scholarships and grants related to all levels of experience to promote scientific mobility of researchers and practitioners in STEM fields.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The Society grants membership to undergraduates as student members provided they can pay the $25 yearly dues.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Any university may start its own ACS Student Chapter and receive benefits of undergraduate participation in regional conferences and discounts on ACS publications.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The American Chemical Society administers 64 national awards, medals and prizes based on scientific contributions at various career levels that promote achievement across the chemical sciences.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS national awards program began in 1922 with the establishment of the Priestley Medal, the highest award offered by the ACS, which is given for distinguished services to chemistry.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Additional awards are offered by divisions, local sections and other bodies of ACS.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Nichols Medal Award was the first ACS award to honor outstanding researchers in the field of chemistry.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] It was established in 1903 by the ACS New York Section and is named for William H.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Nichols, an American chemist and businessman and one of the original founders of ACS.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Of the over 100 Nichols Medalists, 16 have subsequently been awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The Willard Gibbs Award, granted by the ACS Chicago Section, was established in 1910 in honor of Josiah Willard Gibbs, the Yale University professor who formulated the phase rule.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The Georgia Local Section of ACS has awarded the Herty Medal since 1933 recognizing outstanding chemists who have significantly contributed to their chosen fields.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] All chemists in academic, government, or industrial laboratories who have been residing in the southeastern United States for at least 10 years are eligible.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The New York Section of ACS also gives Leadership Awards.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The Leadership Awards are the highest honors given by the Chemical Marketing and Economic Group of ACS NY since December 6, 2012.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] They are presented to leaders of industry, investments, and other sectors, for their contributions to science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) initiatives.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Roy Vagelos (Regeneron, Merck), Thomas M.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Connelly (DuPont) and Juan Pablo del Valle (Mexichem).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS also administers regional awards presented annually at regional meetings.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Ann Nalley Regional Award for Volunteer Service to the American Chemical Society, Regional Awards for Excellence in High School Teaching, and the Stanley C.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] Israel Regional Award for Advancing Diversity in the Chemical Sciences.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] ACS Publications is the publishing division of the ACS.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] It is a nonprofit academic publisher of scientific journals covering various fields of chemistry and related sciences.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In addition to academic journals, ACS Publications also publishes *Chemical & Engineering News*, a weekly trade magazine covering news in the chemical profession, *inChemistry*, a magazine for undergraduate students, and *ChemMatters*, a magazine for high school students and teachers.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] However it has recently launched new open access journals and provided authors with open access publishing options.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In 2006, Congress debated legislation that would have instructed the National Institutes of Health (NIH) to require all investigators it funded to submit copies of final, peer-reviewed journal articles to PubMed Central, a free-access digital repository it operates, within 12 months of publication.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] At the time the American Association of Publishers (of which ACS is a member) hired a public relations firm to counter the open access movement.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In spite of publishers' opposition, the PubMed Central legislation was passed in December 2007 and became effective in 2008.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] As the open access issue has continued to evolve, so too has the ACS's position.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS has also introduced several open access publishing options for its journals, including providing authors the option to pay an upfront fee to enable free online access to their articles.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In 2015, the ACS launched the first fully open access journal in the society's history, *ACS Central Science*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS states that the journal offers the same peer-review standards as its subscription journals, but without publishing charges to either authors or readers.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] A second open access title, *ACS Omega*, an interdisciplinary mega journal, launched in 2016.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In 2005, the ACS was criticized for opposing the creation of PubChem, which is an open access chemical database developed by the NIH's National Center for Biotechnology Information.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS raised concerns that the publicly supported PubChem database would duplicate and unfairly compete with their existing fee-based Chemical Abstracts Service and argued that the database should only present data created by the Molecular Libraries Screening Center initiative of the NIH.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS lobbied members of the United States Congress to rein in PubChem and hired outside lobbying firms to try to persuade congressional members, the NIH, and the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) against establishing a publicly funded database.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS was unsuccessful, and as of 2012 PubChem is the world's largest free chemical database.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS is also the only provider of a major scientific publication database (SciFinder) that imposes a restriction on the number of records that can be exported.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] None of the competing products, such as Web of Science (owned by Clarivate), Scopus (owned by Elsevier) and The Lens (owned by Cambia) have similar restrictions.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS has been involved in numerous lawsuits regarding access to its databases, trademark rights, and copyrighted material.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In many of these cases, the ACS lost or ended up with an unenforceable judgement.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS was also found guilty in several lawsuits brought against the Society by its employees.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] In 2004, a group of ACS members criticized the compensation of former executive director and chief executive officer John Crum, whose total salary, expenses, and bonuses for 2002 was reported to be $767,834.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] The ACS defended the figure, saying that it was in line with that of comparable organizations, including for-profit publishers.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, two employees were reported to have a total compensation exceeding $900,000, while 694 had a compensation exceeding $100,000.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The **American Geophysical Union** (**AGU**) is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization of Earth, atmospheric, ocean, hydrologic, space, and planetary scientists and enthusiasts that according to their website includes 130,000 people (not members).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] AGU's activities are focused on the organization and dissemination of scientific information in the interdisciplinary and international fields within the Earth and space sciences.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The geophysical sciences involve four fundamental areas: atmospheric and ocean sciences; solid-Earth sciences; hydrologic sciences; and space sciences.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The organization's headquarters is located on Florida Avenue in Washington, D.C.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU was established in December 1919 by the National Research Council (NRC) to represent the United States in the International Union of Geodesy and Geophysics (IUGG), and its first chairman was William Bowie of the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey (USCGS).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] For more than 50 years, it operated as an unincorporated affiliate of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] On June 29, 1972, AGU was incorporated in the District of Columbia and membership was opened to scientists and students worldwide.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU was intended to promote "pure" geophysics; exploration geophysics has its own society, the Society of Exploration Geophysicists.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In a March 1919 report by a committee chaired by Robert S.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Woodward of the Carnegie Institution, geophysics was defined as a collection of "borderlands" (closely related, mutually dependent subjects): astronomy, geodesy, geology, meteorology, oceanography, seismology, terrestrial magnetism, terrestrial electricity, tides, and volcanology.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU was organized under seven sections: Geodesy, Seismology, Meteorology, Terrestrial magnetism and electricity, Oceanography, Volcanology, and Geophysical chemistry.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Hydrology was added in 1930 and Tectonophysics in 1940.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The first meeting of the AGU took place on April 23, 1920.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Up to 1930, the number of members was restricted and members were elected.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In 1932 the first annual dues of US$2 were imposed.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The journal *Radio Science* is co-sponsored by the International Union of Radio Science.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The journal *Earth Interactions* is published in partnership with the American Meteorological Society (AMS) and the Association of American Geographers (AAG).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In addition, *International Journal of Geomagnetism and Aeronomy* is no longer published and AGU distributes *Chinese Journal of Geophysics* and *Nonlinear Processes in Geophysics*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Many of the journals have high impact factors, with *Paleoceanography* having the highest within paleontology and *Reviews of Geophysics* the second highest within geochemistry and geophysics as of 2010.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] AGU has also been publishing books for more than 85 years.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] AGU co-published (along with the AMS and the AAG) its first electronic journal, *Earth Interactions*, in 1997.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] It started its own electronic journal, *Geochemistry, Geophysics, Geosystems*, in December 1999.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] It made a full transition to electronic publishing in 2001.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] For all its journals, the electronic version became the publication of record.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] This was accompanied by a new identification scheme for articles that entirely did away with sequential page numbers.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Instead, each article had a digital object identifier (DOI).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] This new system was met with complaints from libraries and scientists.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The article numbers provided no clue for libraries to find an article in printed versions, and even scientific databases were not set up to handle DOIs.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] AGU officials claimed that the problems were a temporary cost of being a frontrunner, but did retroactively assign each article a four-digit article number.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In 2012 the journals and books, including over one and a half million pages of legacy content, were transferred to the Wiley Online Library.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] John Wiley & Sons were recognized for this work with the IT Project Team of the Year Award at the UK IT Industry Awards for 2013.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Five AGU journals are open access only: *AGU Advances*, *Earth’s Future*, *Earth and Space Science*, *GeoHealth*, *JAMES*, and *Space Weather*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The remainder are delayed open access journals, having free access after a two-year rolling period.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU hosts a number of blogs, collectively known as the AGU Blogosphere, informally publishing frequent updates on the Earth and space sciences.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] AGU publications are copyrighted, but in the United States many exceptions to the exclusive rights of copyright are allowed under the fair use provision, part of the Copyright Act of 1976.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Making copies of publications are allowed for such uses as teaching and research as long as a set of four criteria are met.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] However, when Texaco's corporate library made systematic copies of journal articles for its collection, AGU and five other publishers took Texaco to court.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Texaco was fined and agreed to retroactively purchase a license from the Copyright Clearance Center.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] While more than 40 presidents have provided scientific leadership for the AGU since 1919, operational leadership has been provided by a larger team.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The first senior team member was John Adam Fleming, who was elected Secretary in 1925 and changed the name of his position to General Secretary.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] He served as a volunteer while working at the Department of Terrestrial Magnetism at the Carnegie Institution.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] By 1943, with the membership nearing 2,000, AGU recognized the need for a full-time professional administrator.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The post was renamed Executive Secretary and Waldo E.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] He served until 1970 and then Athelstan Spilhaus, Jr. was hired as executive director.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Medals have been named after Fleming and Smith.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU leadership in 2021 included, in addition to the president, a CEO, 4 executive vice presidents, 6 vice presidents, 7 directors, and a chief digital officer.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU offers several awards, medals and fellowships.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] AGU nominates members for fellowship in the society.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU is divided into 25 sections that provide the main structure for managing volunteers, developing leaders and honoring scientists.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] AGU holds an annual meeting every December (known as the Fall Meeting).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Until 2017, the meeting was held yearly in San Francisco.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Because of renovations at the San Francisco venue, the 2017 meeting took place in New Orleans and the 2018 meeting in Washington, DC.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] It returned to San Francisco in 2019 and its location will rotate among San Francisco, New Orleans, Chicago, and Washington, DC.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Previously, a second meeting was held every Spring (April through May) in locations around the world.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The latter grew out of AGU's annual Spring meeting, which had been held for many years in Baltimore, until declining interest caused AGU to move the meeting to different locations, starting with Boston in 1998.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] With the 2003 meeting in Nice, France, it became known as the Joint Assembly because AGU co-sponsors it with other societies such as the Geochemical Society, the Mineralogical Society of America (MSA), the Canadian Geophysical Union (CGU), and the European Geosciences Union (EGU).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The Fall Meeting had more than 25,000 attendees in 2018.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In addition to the Fall meeting that covers all areas of the geophysical sciences, AGU sponsors many specialized meetings that are intended to serve the needs of particular scientific disciplines or geographical areas, including the Ocean Sciences Meeting, which is held in even numbered years.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Small, highly focused meetings are offered through the Chapman Conferences.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The large numbers and international participation in the Fall Meeting results in a large contribution to greenhouse gases.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The 9500 participants in the 2002 meeting traveled an average of 8,000 kilometres (5,000 mi) to attend, producing 1.3 metric tons of carbon dioxide, or one-sixteenth of the average yearly emissions for Americans.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU has made some adjustments such as asking shuttle bus drivers to turn off their engines when they are not moving, but 95% of the emissions come from jet fuel.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In an unpublished study, David Scott and Lawrence Plug of Dalhousie University estimated that the AGU could reduce emissions by 7.7% if it moved the Fall Meeting to Denver, Colorado.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In 2017, the first joint JpGU-AGU meeting was held in Chiba, Japan.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The meeting was a joint effort between AGU and the Japan Geoscience Union.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] On occasion the AGU Council issues position statements on matters affecting public policy that are related to geophysics.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] These include biological evolution, natural hazards, science education and funding, and climate change.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU adopted its first position statement on climate change in December 1998.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The adopted position statement was backed up by a detailed supporting document.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU position statement has undergone several revisions, most recently revised and reaffirmed in 2012.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In 2014, AGU developed the Sharing Science program to provide scientists with the skills and tools that they need to communicate science with any audience.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The program offers resources, workshops, hands-on support, and opportunities to help scientists more effectively communicate with broader audiences about Earth and space science.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Audiences range from journalists, educators and students, policy makers, and the broader public.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Members of the AGU who work in politically controversial fields have come under legal attack.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] However, such legal challenges continue, so in 2012 AGU entered in a partnership with the Climate Science Legal Defense Fund to offer legal counseling at the Fall Meeting.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Gleick, a climate scientist and recipient of the MacArthur Fellowship, said he was motivated by frustration with the efforts of groups such as the Heartland Institute to attack climate science and scientists, but admitted that it was a serious lapse of judgement.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] He resigned from the task force on February 16, 2012, and was replaced by Linda Gundersen, director of the Office of Science Quality and Integrity at the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In 2017, AGU adopted and updated ethics policy, called the AGU Scientific Integrity and Professional Ethics.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Among other updates, the policy updated its definitions of what counts as scientific misconduct to include harassment, bullying, and discrimination.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Additionally, AGU staff are trained in how to address incidents of harassment at their annual meeting and wear "Safe AGU" buttons to signify themselves as resources.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] On February 27, 2018, AGU CEO Chris McEntee testified before the House Committee on Science, Space, & Technology Subcommittee on Research and Technology Hearing – A Review of Sexual Harassment and Misconduct in Science.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] His testimony was alongside those of Rhonda Davis, head of the National Science Foundation's (NSF) Office of Diversity and Inclusion, Kathryn Clancy, an anthropologist at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, and attorney Kristina Larsen.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In July 2019, the AGU was awarded a three-year grant from the Alfred P.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Sloan Foundation to launch the AGU Ethics and Equity Initiative, a collaboration among the AGU and the National Center for Professional and Research Ethics at the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The initiative will tackle issues around sexual harassment and gender-based discrimination by developing new educational resources and tracking tools to measure impact.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In December 2022, AGU punished climate scientists Rose Abramoff and Peter Kalmus for misconduct, who interrupted a plenary session of the annual Fall Meeting with a call for scientists to engage in protest against climate change.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] AGU removed their research presentations from the meeting, banned them from participation, launched a misconduct inquiry, and complained to Abramoff's employer, Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Kalmus and Abramoff further claimed that AGU threatened to have them arrested if they returned to the meeting.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Abramoff was fired by Oak Ridge in January 2023.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In 2014, the AGU accepted 5469 gifts, grants and pledges from individuals and corporations.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Of these, the 1919 Society (gifts of over $100,000) included ExxonMobil, Integrated Ocean Drilling Program Management International, and Nature's Own.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] AGU also was found to have many annual events sponsored by corporations, including an annual Student Breakfast (supported by ExxonMobil) and Amazon Web Services supported research grants and that offer access to its cloud computing resources.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In 2015, the AGU Board approved a new Organizational Support Policy.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The policy covers subjects such as advertorials and member surveys.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The sponsorship of AGU by ExxonMobil became a source of concern for many members after evidence surfaced that ExxonMobil had known about climate change for decades but had actively worked to undermine climate science.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] On February 22, 2016, a letter signed by 100 scientists was delivered to the AGU, requesting that they cut all ties with ExxonMobil and other companies that foster climate misinformation.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The AGU Board of Directors met on April 22, 2016, and voted to continue accepting sponsorship from ExxonMobil, arguing that there was not unequivocal evidence that ExxonMobil continues to participate in climate misinformation.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] Instead of making a short-term political statement, the Board wished to engage with the energy industry over the long term.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] In response, Senator Sheldon Whitehouse and Representative Ted Lieu sent a critical letter saying that ExxonMobil continues to fund climate denial and is misleading the AGU.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] The Union of Concerned Scientists also sent a letter urging them to reconsider.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geophysical-union] However, in a meeting on September 23, 2016, the Board upheld its previous decision.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] The **American Geosciences Institute** (**AGI**) is a nonprofit federation of about 50 geoscientific and professional organizations that represents geologists, geophysicists, and other earth scientists.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] The organization's offices are in Alexandria, Virginia.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] The name of the organization was changed from the **American Geological Institute** on October 1, 2011.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] Since 1966, AGI has produced GeoRef, a literature database for those studying the earth sciences.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] AGI operates the Center for Geosciences and Society.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] AGI's monthly magazine *Geotimes* became *EARTH Magazine* on September 1, 2008, with an increased focus on public communication of geoscience research.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] In April 2019, *EARTH Magazine* suspended publication and was folded into *Nautilus Quarterly*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] The stated mission of AGI is to "represent and serve the geoscience community by providing collaborative leadership and information to connect Earth, science, and people".
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] GeoRef offers a variety of specialized databases for researchers, educators, and students in specific areas of geoscience.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] AGI offers lessons and curricula designed for teachers of Earth sciences in schools (K-12).
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] These educational resources are created in partnership with geological organizations whose work is related to Earth science concepts.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] Every year in the second full week of October, AGI runs Earth Science Week, to promote understanding of Earth science and stewardship of the planet.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] The Geological Society of America (GSA) and the National Cooperative Geological Mapping Program of the U.S.
[src:donald-i-siegel/american-geosciences-institute] Geological Survey hold the Annual Best Student Geologic Map Competition to bring together student geologic mappers from around the world.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Ari Shapiro was born in Fargo, North Dakota, the son of Elayne (née Halpern), a university communications professor, and Leonard Shapiro, a database researcher and university teacher.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] When he was eight years old, he moved with his family to Beaverton, Oregon.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] He graduated magna cum laude from Yale University in 2000 with a Bachelor of Arts degree in English.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] At Yale, he sang in Mixed Company of Yale and was a member of the Scroll and Key secret society.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Shapiro began his NPR career as an intern to legal affairs correspondent Nina Totenberg in January 2001.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Following that assignment, he worked as an editorial assistant and an assistant editor on *Morning Edition*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] After working as a regional reporter for NPR in Atlanta and Miami and five years as NPR's Justice Correspondent, Shapiro began covering the White House in 2010.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] In 2014, he became NPR's correspondent in London.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] On July 9, 2015, NPR announced that Shapiro and Kelly McEvers would join Audie Cornish and Robert Siegel as hosts of NPR's *All Things Considered* program.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Since 2009, Shapiro has been a regular guest singer with the band Pink Martini.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] He appears on four of the band's albums, singing in several languages.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] He made his live debut with the band at the Hollywood Bowl.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] He has performed live with them frequently since then, including at such venues as Carnegie Hall and the Beacon Theatre in New York City, Kennedy Center in Washington, D.C., the Olympia in Paris, Kew Gardens in London, and the Lycabettus Theatre in Athens.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] In 2019, Shapiro embarked on a cabaret career, joining Alan Cumming for a show called *Och & Oy!
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] A Considered Cabaret* with performances in Fire Island and Provincetown.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Och & Oy has gone on to tour the United States including performances at the Kennedy Center and the Cafe Carlyle.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Shapiro has also done solo cabaret performances around the United States, including in such venues as Joe's Pub and 54 Below.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] In 2023, Harper Collins published his debut memoir, *The Best Strangers in the World: Stories from a Life Spent Listening*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] It became an instant *New York Times* bestseller and was described by Kirkus reviews as "a clever and compulsively readable crowd pleaser".
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] In 2024, Shapiro was announced as the host of the seventh season, and the second by Netflix, of the reality TV series *The Mole*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] In 2025, Shapiro announced he would be leaving his role at NPR.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Shapiro has won three national Edward R.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Murrow awards; one for a global series that connected the dots between climate change, migration, and far-right political leaders; another for his reporting on the life and death of Breonna Taylor; and the third for his coverage of the Trump Administration's asylum policies on the US-Mexico border.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Shapiro was the first NPR reporter to be promoted to correspondent before age 30.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] In May 2010, the pop-culture magazine *Paper* included Shapiro in an annual list of "Beautiful People", saying he "must have a clone.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] In 2016 and 2008, LGBT-themed magazine *Out* included Shapiro in the "Out 100", a list of "the year's most interesting, influential, and newsworthy LGBT people".
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Shapiro was also included on a list of openly gay media professionals in *The Advocate*'s "Forty under 40" issue of June/July 2009.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] In 2023, Shapiro received a Doctor of Humane Letters honorary degree from the University of Portland.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] On February 27, 2004, Shapiro and longtime boyfriend Michael Gottlieb were married at San Francisco City Hall.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Gottlieb is a lawyer who worked in the office of the White House Counsel from 2013 to 2015.
[src:donald-i-siegel/ari-shapiro] Shapiro and Susan Stamberg, the first co-host of *All Things Considered,* are cousins.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] The web-based service of the CBC is one of Canada's most visited web sites.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] It currently contains over one million pages of information.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] The CBC also runs the French-language website **Ici.Radio-Canada.ca**.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In 1993, the CBC launched an experimental web service, followed by a small site supporting CBC Radio and a site supporting the CBC Halifax TV program *Street Cents*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] By 1995, the CBC had consolidated its English radio and TV sites into a single website.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] Around 1996, the CBC began offering 24-hour live streaming of its radio services using RealAudio.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] The next year, the CBC launched CBC Kids and covered its first federal election online.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] The CBC launched its news site the following year.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In 2000, the CBC launched a wireless service and CBC Radio 3, an Internet-exclusive broadband magazine.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] Radio 3 provides streaming audio devoted to youth culture and independent music and is operated by CBC Radio.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In 2001, cbc.ca finished a major redesign that modernized the news portal and earned an English Television Award.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In 2005, production of the Radio 3 magazine was suspended, although the site continues in podcast format.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] Some of its programming still aired as a Saturday-evening show on CBC Radio Two until March 2007.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] *Bande à part* is the French equivalent and also airs content as a weekend program on *Espace Musique*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] Both services launched as full channels on Sirius Canada in December 2005 and are also available to U.S.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] Radio-Canada.ca is the French Language online service run by Société Radio-Canada, the French counterpart of the CBC.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In June 2013, the CBC announced that Radio-Canada's website was to be moved to **ICI.ca** in October 2013, as part of wide plan to re-brand all of the CBC's French-language outlets under a common brand, replacing "Radio-Canada" with "Ici" as its main public-facing brand.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] However, following public backlash for its decision to drop the historic Radio-Canada name, the site has maintained its current domain name, but is branded in logos as ici.radio-canada.ca, and Ici.ca redirects to the site.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] The websites include news from the CBC News website, an extensive sports section, music, science, technology and entertainment pages.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] CBC/Radio-Canada also offers an extensive, free archives service showcasing pivotal moments in Canadian history from the 1930s on.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] Over 8,000 online clips and interviews from news and information programs provide an in-depth look at Canada's past.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In 2004, the CBC began offering RSS feeds, and in 2005, it launched a new online arts and entertainment magazine.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In 2006, CBC.ca underwent another redesign after extensive study, with improvements to standards compliance.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In March 2008, the website added a comments section to most news items, allowing feedback on stories.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In 2005, the CBC began podcasting some of its programs as a pilot project, including CBC Radio One's national science and technology program, *Quirks and Quarks*, CBC Radio 3's *Canadian Music Podcast*, and limited podcasting of CBLA's popular *Metro Morning* show.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In May 2006, the CBC added several more podcasts, including *Dispatches*, best-of editions of *Outfront*, *As It Happens*, *Ideas*, *The Current* and *Definitely Not the Opera*, weekly podcasts from regional radio stations and *Editor's Choice*, a daily showcase of notable network programming.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In 2003, the CBC won an Online News Association award in the "service journalism" category for its coverage of the SARS epidemic.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] CBC.ca was also a finalist in the "online commentary" category for "Words: Woes and Wonder", a series of columns about the English language.
[src:donald-i-siegel/cbc-ca] In 2007, CBCNews.ca won the 2006 RTNDA award for best overall use of new media in Canada.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] Siegel earned his Bachelors in Geology at University of Rhode Island in 1969.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] He earned his MS at Penn State and PhD in Hydrogeology at University of Minnesota.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] Siegel began his career at Amerada Hess Corporation in 1971 as an exploration geologist, conducting geological studies to locate oil and gas in the Rocky Mountains and southwestern United States.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] He moved to the United States Geological Survey in 1976 as a district hydrogeologist in the Minnesota District.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] In 1982, he became an assistant professor at the College of Arts and Sciences at Syracuse University, becoming a full professor in 1992.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] Siegel was appointed department chair in 2013 and worked at Syracuse until his retirement in 2017.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] He was also the *Jessie Page Heroy Professor* and a *Meredith Professor of Teaching Excellence (2009)*.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] While working as a USGS hydrologist, after making his early observations on deep groundwater deposits, Siegel discovered that groundwater flow regulates the diversity of habitats in the mires, world's largest wetlands.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] He also studied interaction of oil-spill organic matter with minerals in affected aquifers, interaction of this groundwater with wetlands, and the westernmost edge where acid rain was being deposited by coal-fired power plants.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] After joining the faculty at Syracuse, Siegel studied of how groundwater and deep saline waters passed through the Marcellus Shale millions of years ago to the present.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] Siegel's wetland research evolved into an examination of how groundwater flow and water quality influences greenhouse gas emissions in vast peat lands in northern Canada, Siberia, and northern Minnesota.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] His early study of groundwater contamination resulted in the closure of Staten Island's Fresh Kills Landfill.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] Siegel also investigated the use of similar forensic techniques to characterize fluids generated by hydraulic fracking and other unconventional gas and oil extraction in western China, Pennsylvania, Ohio, and New York State.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] Siegel has said that hydrofracking benefits in New York state outweigh the environmental risks, calling it a safe process.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] In 2015, Siegel was involved in a conflict-of-interest controversy.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] In a peer reviewed paper, Siegel came to a conclusion that natural-gas production using fracking wells had not contaminated groundwater in Pennsylvania and that methane in drinking water was unrelated to fracking.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] After media reports that Siegel did not disclose that Chesapeake Energy, a hydrocarbon exploration company, had paid him to analyze the data, the journal Environmental Science & Technology, which published the analysis, posted a correction.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] While fracking proponents praised the study, many environmental groups ethical violations and cited smaller sample size that had produced conflicting results.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] Despite Siegel's admission of private funding, he received intense backlash.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] Critics demanded that he be fired or retire from Syracuse University, and that an ethics investigation be launched by both SU and the journal.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] The university later found that Siegel was in compliance with University's internal disclosure policies.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] In 2015, Siegel was called to testify before the Committee on Science, Space, and Technology in Washington, D.C.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] The Hydrogeology Division of the Geological Society of America selected Siegel as the 1993 Birdsall Distinguished Lecturer in Hydrogeology.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] He was elected and served as the 1995 Chairman of the Hydrogeology Division of the GSA.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] He is a recipient of the Geological Society of American’s Distinguished Service Award.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] In 2005, Siegel received the Meinzer Award for Research by the Hydrogeology Division of the Geological Society of America.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] In 2010, Siegel was appointed chair of the Water Sciences & Technology Board for a three year term.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] In 2012, Siegel was elected member of the American Association for the Advancement of Science for "his distinguished service and pioneering contributions on the hydrogeology and biogeochemistry of wetlands and contaminant transport".
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] He was elected a fellow of the American Geophysical Union in 2013.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] Siegel served as the president of the Geological Society of America from July 2019 until June 2020.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] In 2022, he was awarded the Marcus Milling Legendary Geoscientist Medal by the American Geosciences Institute.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] Siegel was born on October 24, 1947, into a Jewish family in New York City.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] He lives in Syracuse with his wife Bette Siegel.
[src:donald-i-siegel/donald-i-siegel] In 2005, he wrote a cookbook titled *"From Lokshen to Lo Mein: The Jewish Love Affair With Chinese Food"* (Gefen, ISBN 9789652293572).
